Creating an interactive chatbot with a modal in HTML requires using JavaScript and CSS for the modal functionality and a bit of HTML to structure the content. Below is a simple example using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Keep in mind that this is a basic implementation and might need adjustments for a production-ready application.

HTML (index.html):

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Fake Chatbot</title>
    <style>
        #modal {
            display: none;
            position: fixed;
            z-index: 1;
            left: 0;
            top: 0;
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
            overflow: auto;
            background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
        }

        #chatHistory {
            height: 400px;
            overflow-y: scroll;
        }

        #chatHistory p {
            margin-bottom: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="openModal">Open Chat History</button>
    <div id="modal" class="modal">
        <div id="chatHistory">
            <p>User: Hi, how are you?</p>
            <p>Bot: I'm doing great, thanks! How about you?</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

JavaScript (script.js):

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
    const openModalBtn = document.getElementById('openModal');
    const modal = document.getElementById('modal');
    const chatHistory = document.getElementById('chatHistory');

    openModalBtn.addEventListener('click', function () {
        modal.style.display = 'block';
    });

    function closeModal() {
        modal.style.display = 'none';
    }

    chatHistory.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
        if (e.target.tagName === 'P') {
            const messageElement = e.target.parentElement;
            const humanMessage = messageElement.textContent;

            const botResponse = generateBotResponse(humanMessage);
            const botMessage = document.createElement('p');
            botMessage.textContent = botResponse;

            chatHistory.appendChild(botMessage);
        }
    });

    function generateBotResponse(humanMessage) {
        // Simulate a bot response
        return `Bot: ${humanMessage} (AI)`;
    }

    function closeModal() {
        modal.style.display = 'none';
    }
});
```

This simple example creates a modal with an input for a history chat. When the user clicks the "Open Chat History" button, the modal appears, showing two previous messages (one from the human and one from the bot). The bot's responses are dynamically generated by the `generateBotResponse` function and appended to the chat history. When the user clicks anywhere outside of the modal, it closes the modal.

Note: This is a very basic implementation to demonstrate the concept. A production-ready solution would likely require more advanced logic and user experience design.

