To draw a chessboard using FEN notation in LaTeX, you can use the "chessboard" package by Tigris. Here's a step-by-step guide to create the board and a LATEX code with the required commands.

1. First, add the chessboard package to your document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
```

2. To define custom chess piece symbols, add these commands in the preamble:

```latex
\chessboardStyle{FEN1}{% FEN1 notations}
\setchessboardcolors{white}{white}{black}

\defchesspiece{\Rook}{\Large\bfseries\ding{172}}
\defchesspiece{\Knight}{\large\ding{168}}
\defchesspiece{\Bishop}{\large\ding{160}}
\defchesspiece{\Queen}{\large\ding{161}}
\defchesspiece{\King}{\large\ding{163}}
\defchesspiece{\Pawn}{\large\ding{182}}

\chessboardset{2}{% Set the board size (width and height)
  a1 a2 b1 b2 c1 c2 d1 d2 e1 e2 f1 f2
}

\chessboarddefaultstyle{1}
\chessboardset{1}{% Set the board style
  alternating
}
```

3. Now, add the main code to draw the chessboard with FEN notation:

```latex
\begin{chessboard}
  \foreach \x in {1,...,8} {
    \foreach \y in {1,...,8} {
      \ifodd\x \even\y
        \put\chessboardcell[\x*1.5cm,y*1.5cm]{\Rook}
      \else
        \put\chessboardcell[\x*1.5cm,y*1.5cm]{\Knight}
